  <section class="disclaimer"> <p><em>This guide is for informational purposes only. Consult a financial advisor with cannabis industry experience for guidance on your specific situation.</em></p> </section> <section> <h2>Credit Unions in Maine That Serve Cannabis</h2> <p>Maine credit unions have been more willing than national banks to serve cannabis businesses. The key is finding a credit union with an established cannabis banking program rather than one that is experimenting with the market.</p> <p>When evaluating credit unions, ask specific questions about their cannabis banking policies. How many cannabis clients do they currently serve? What documentation do they require for account opening? What are their ongoing compliance expectations? What happens to your account if their risk posture changes? Answers to these questions reveal whether a credit union is genuinely committed to cannabis banking or merely testing the waters.</p> <p>Service limitations often apply even at cannabis-friendly credit unions. Some limit transaction volume, cap account balances, or require additional collateral for business lines of credit. Understanding these limitations before opening an account prevents operational surprises when you need to process larger transactions.</p> <p>Relationship building matters in Maine's credit union market. Smaller credit unions often make decisions based on personal relationships and community standing. Visiting branches in person, meeting with relationship managers, and demonstrating that you are a committed local business operator improves your chances of account approval.</p> </section> <section> <h2>Cash Management for Maine Cannabis Operations</h2> <p>Most Maine cannabis dispensaries handle significant cash volumes. Cash management requires documented procedures, secure storage, and organized banking routines that minimize risk exposure.</p> <p>Safe selection matters for cannabis retail. The safe must be heavy enough to resist removal, certified for cash storage by recognized testing agencies, and equipped with time-delay mechanisms that prevent after-hours theft. Budget $3,000-$8,000 for a compliant safe with appropriate rating for your cash volumes.</p> <p>Armored car services provide secure transport but cost $500-$2,000 monthly depending on pickup frequency and cash volumes. Establish regular schedules so staff know when to prepare deposits. Some operators reduce armored car costs by consolidating deposits and using the service less frequently when cash volumes are lower.</p> <p>Cash reconciliation procedures should happen daily. Designate specific staff responsible for counting and recording cash receipts. Reconcile against POS records daily to catch discrepancies while same-day memory remains fresh. Document every reconciliation with signed records that demonstrate accountability.</p> </section> <section> <h2>280E Banking Strategy for Maine Operators</h2> <p>The intersection of 280E tax treatment and banking limitations creates planning challenges that require integrated strategy. Your banking approach affects your tax situation in ways that may not be obvious.</p> <p>Expense documentation becomes critical under 280E. Every business expenditure must be traceable to verifiable records. Cash purchases without receipts create audit risk because you cannot prove the expenditure was for ordinary business purposes. Using bank accounts for as many transactions as possible strengthens your documentation trail.</p> <p>Cost of goods sold calculation depends on accurate inventory tracking. Banking relationships that allow electronic inventory purchasing through verified merchant accounts create better documentation than cash purchasing from cultivators. Even with limited banking access, push vendors to provide electronic payment options where possible.</p> <p>Reserve management affects tax exposure. Maintaining large cash reserves reduces your taxable income but also reduces your available working capital. Work with your CPA to balance reserve levels against tax savings. The difference between 30 days and 90 days of reserves may represent significant tax exposure.</p> </section> </article> 
